<paragraph id="A770368FBA36B929FF72F90DFDCFF858" blockId="1.[151,1436,1730,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="441">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA36B929FF72F90DFEC2F95C" bold="true" box="[151,359,1730,1757]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="441">Generic diagnosis</emphasis>
modified from 
<bibRefCitation id="C35E4B7EBA36B929FDF2F90DFD77F95C" author="Williams, D. J." box="[535,722,1731,1757]" pageId="1" pageNumber="441" refId="ref6423" refString="Williams, D. J. (2004) Mealybugs of southern Asia. The Natural History Museum. Southdene SDN. BHD., Kuala Lumpur, 896 pp." type="book" year="2004">Williams (2004)</bibRefCitation>
. Body of adult female rotund, hemispherical, becoming heavily sclerotized with maturity. Anal lobes absent. Antennae plate-like. Eyes absent. Clypeolabral shield of mouthparts with long internal anterior extension. Legs absent; positions of hind legs each indicated by sac-like area containing numerous duct-like pores. Spiracles well developed. Circulus and ostioles absent. Anal ring complete, circular, bearing pores and more than 15 setae, situated on dorsum well anterior to apex of abdomen. Vulva slit-like, opening directed posteriorly. Dorsum with dense long slender setae, especially on medial area. Trilocular and discoidal pores abundant on both surfaces. Multilocular disc pores numerous on venter and a few present on dorsum. Oral rim tubular ducts and oral collar ducts absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A770368FBA35B92AFF22FF59FDB6FEE4" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1005]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Body of first-instar nymph broadly oval. Anal lobes not developed. Antennae each 6-segmented. Eyes present. Legs well developed, tarsal and claw digitules present, knobbed. Circulus present. Single pore-like structure present lateral to each hind coxa. Ostioles present or absent. Anal ring complete, bearing more than 15 setae, situated on dorsum anterior to apex of abdomen. Setae flagellate, abundant on both surfaces but particularly so in medial area of dorsum. Trilocular and discoidal pores scattered amongst body setae. Multilocular disc pores, oral rim tubular ducts and oral collar ducts absent.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A770368FBA35B92AFF22FEA0FA84FC6C" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1005]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFF22FEA0FECCFE09" bold="true" box="[199,361,366,392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Relationships</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="C35E4B7EBA35B92AFE9DFEA1FD97FE08" author="Williams, D. J." box="[376,562,367,393]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" refId="ref6423" refString="Williams, D. J. (2004) Mealybugs of southern Asia. The Natural History Museum. Southdene SDN. BHD., Kuala Lumpur, 896 pp." type="book" year="2004">Williams (2004)</bibRefCitation>
considered the genus 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFCD7FEA1FC38FE09" authorityName="Newstead" authorityYear="1897" box="[818,925,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Kermicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFCD7FEA1FC38FE09" box="[818,925,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Kermicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be closely related to genus 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFB1AFEA1FE99FE2C" authority="Maskell, 1898" authorityName="Maskell" authorityYear="1898" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Chaetococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFB1AFEA1FA39FE08" box="[1279,1436,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Chaetococcus</emphasis>
Maskell, 1898
</taxonomicName>
. In the tribe 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFE34FE5DFDDCFE2C" box="[465,633,403,429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" rank="tribe" tribe="Serrolecaniiini">Serrolecaniiini</taxonomicName>
, adult females were described by 
<bibRefCitation id="C35E4B7EBA35B92AFBE5FE5DFAD7FE2C" author="Hendricks, H. &amp; Kosztarab, M. P." box="[1024,1394,403,429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" refId="ref6276" refString="Hendricks, H. &amp; Kosztarab, M. P. (1999) Revision of the Tribe Serrolecaniini (Homoptera: Pseudococcidae). de Gruyter, Berlin and New York, xiv + 213 pp." type="book" year="1999">Hendricks and Kosztarab (1999)</bibRefCitation>
for 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFF72FE79FD8EFE53" authority="(Maskell)" authorityName="Coccoidea" baseAuthorityName="Maskell" baseAuthorityYear="1892" box="[151,555,439,466]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Chaetococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bambusae">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFF72FE79FE14FE50" box="[151,433,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Chaetococcus bambusae</emphasis>
(Maskell)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFDDFFE79FB86FE50" authority="Takahashi &amp; Kanda" authorityName="Takahashi &amp; Kanda" authorityYear="1939" box="[570,1059,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Idiococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bambusae">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFDDFFE79FC94FE50" box="[570,817,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Idiococcus bambusae</emphasis>
Takahashi &amp; Kanda
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFBD7FE79FA3DFE50" authority="(Kuwana)" baseAuthorityName="Kuwana" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[1074,1432,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Serrolecanium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tobai">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFBD7FE79FABEFE50" box="[1074,1307,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Serrolecanium tobai</emphasis>
