</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="C35E4B7EBA35B92AFB9BFDEDFA9DFDBC" author="Williams, D. J." box="[1150,1336,547,573]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" refId="ref6423" refString="Williams, D. J. (2004) Mealybugs of southern Asia. The Natural History Museum. Southdene SDN. BHD., Kuala Lumpur, 896 pp." type="book" year="2004">Williams (2004)</bibRefCitation>
, the 
<typeStatus id="7874882DBA35B92AFA89FDEDFA39FDBC" box="[1388,1436,547,573]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">type</typeStatus>
species of genus 
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFEB3FD89FE13FDE1" box="[342,438,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Kermicu</emphasis>
s. The first-instar nymphs were described by Yang &amp; Kosztarab (1967) for 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFB1AFD89FEACFD04" authorityName="Coccoidea" baseAuthorityName="Maskell" baseAuthorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Chaetococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bambusae">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFB1AFD89FEACFD04" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Chaetococcus bambusae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; by 
<bibRefCitation id="C35E4B7EBA35B92AFEDEFDA5FE60FD04" author="Tang, F. T." box="[315,453,619,645]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" pagination="393 - 399" refId="ref6340" refString="Tang, F. T. (1984) Discovery of a new species of Idiococcus and discussion on the systematic status of this genus. Verhandlungen Des Zehnten Internationalen Symposiums Uber Entomofaunistik Mitteleuropas (SIEEC), 10, 393 - 399." type="journal article" year="1984">Tang (1984)</bibRefCitation>
for 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFE11FDA5FC0BFD04" authority="Tang &amp; Wu" authorityName="Tang &amp; Wu" box="[500,942,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Idiococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maanshanensis">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFE11FDA5FC85FD04" box="[500,800,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Idiococcus maanshanensis</emphasis>
Tang &amp; Wu
</taxonomicName>
; by 
<bibRefCitation id="C35E4B7EBA35B92AFC39FDA5FB31FD04" author="Williams, D. J." box="[988,1172,619,645]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" refId="ref6423" refString="Williams, D. J. (2004) Mealybugs of southern Asia. The Natural History Museum. Southdene SDN. BHD., Kuala Lumpur, 896 pp." type="book" year="2004">Williams (2004)</bibRefCitation>
for 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFB26FDA5FAC1FD04" authorityName="Newstead" authorityYear="1897" box="[1219,1380,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Kermicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wroughtoni">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFB26FDA5FAC1FD04" box="[1219,1380,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">K. wroughtoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and by 
<bibRefCitation id="C35E4B7EBA35B92AFF5CFD41FE94FD28" author="Wu, S. A." box="[185,305,654,681]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" pagination="89 - 90" refId="ref6454" refString="Wu, S. A. (2005) Morphological descriptions on immature stages of Porisaccus jiuhuaensis (Wu) and the origin of bag-like ap- pendage (Homoptera: Pseudococcidae). Journal of Beijing Forestry University, 27 (6), 89 - 90." type="journal article" year="2005">Wu (2005)</bibRefCitation>
for 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFEBBFD41FDC4FD28" box="[350,609,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Porisaccus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jiuhuaensis">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFEBBFD41FDC4FD28" box="[350,609,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Porisaccus jiuhuaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Based on the morphologies of the adult female and first-instar nymph described in the literature, here we suggest that the genera 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFCF5FD7DFBCBFD4C" authority="Takahashi &amp; Kanda" authorityName="Takahashi &amp; Kanda" authorityYear="1939" box="[784,1134,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Idiococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFCF5FD7DFC2CFD4C" box="[784,905,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Idiococcus</emphasis>
Takahashi &amp; Kanda
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFB40FD7DFE80FD70" authority="Hendricks &amp; Kosztarab" authorityName="Hendricks &amp; Kosztarab" authorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Porisaccus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFB40FD7DFA84FD4D" box="[1189,1313,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Porisaccus</emphasis>
Hendricks &amp; Kosztarab
</taxonomicName>
are more closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFDBDFD19FD66FD71" authorityName="Newstead" authorityYear="1897" box="[600,707,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Kermicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFDBDFD19FD66FD71" box="[600,707,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Kermicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than is 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFCFCFD19FC13FD70" authorityName="Maskell" authorityYear="1898" box="[793,950,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Chaetococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFCFCFD19FC13FD70" box="[793,950,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Chaetococcus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, since 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFBE1FD19FB60FD70" box="[1028,1221,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Idiococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maanshanensis">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFBE1FD19FB60FD70" box="[1028,1221,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">I. maanshanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFB36FD19FACBFD70" box="[1235,1390,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Porisaccus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jiuhuaensis">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFB36FD19FACBFD70" box="[1235,1390,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">P. jiuhuaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFF72FD35FE92FC94" authorityName="Newstead" authorityYear="1897" box="[151,311,763,789]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Kermicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wroughtoni">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFF72FD35FE92FC94" box="[151,311,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">K. wroughtoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share with the following features: (1) adult female lacking tubular ducts and possessing a bag-like or sac structure densely covered with duct-like pores in the position of each hind leg; (2) first-instar nymphs all having the same trilocular pore structure (
<bibRefCitation id="C35E4B7EBA35B92AFDC4FC8DFD00FCDC" author="Tang, F. T." box="[545,677,835,861]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" pagination="393 - 399" refId="ref6340" refString="Tang, F. T. (1984) Discovery of a new species of Idiococcus and discussion on the systematic status of this genus. Verhandlungen Des Zehnten Internationalen Symposiums Uber Entomofaunistik Mitteleuropas (SIEEC), 10, 393 - 399." type="journal article" year="1984">Tang, 1984</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="C35E4B7EBA35B92AFD57FC8DFBB9FCDC" author="Hendricks, H. &amp; Kosztarab, M. P." box="[690,1052,835,861]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" refId="ref6276" refString="Hendricks, H. &amp; Kosztarab, M. P. (1999) Revision of the Tribe Serrolecaniini (Homoptera: Pseudococcidae). de Gruyter, Berlin and New York, xiv + 213 pp." type="book" year="1999">Hendricks and Kosztarab, 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="C35E4B7EBA35B92AFBCCFC8DFB38FCDC" author="Wu, S. A." box="[1065,1181,834,861]" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" pagination="89 - 90" refId="ref6454" refString="Wu, S. A. (2005) Morphological descriptions on immature stages of Porisaccus jiuhuaensis (Wu) and the origin of bag-like ap- pendage (Homoptera: Pseudococcidae). Journal of Beijing Forestry University, 27 (6), 89 - 90." type="journal article" year="2005">Wu, 2005</bibRefCitation>
). In contrast, the adult female of 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFEE2FCA9FE02FC00" authorityName="Coccoidea" baseAuthorityName="Maskell" baseAuthorityYear="1892" box="[263,423,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Chaetococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bambusae">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFEE2FCA9FE02FC00" box="[263,423,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">Ch. bambusae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a plate-like structure in the position of each hind leg instead of a bag-like structure, and the first-instar nymph has a different trilocular pore structure from that found in 
<taxonomicName id="60CF4D0CBA35B92AFBF3FC45FF7EFC4B" authority="(Yang &amp; Kosztarab, 1967)" baseAuthorityName="Yang &amp; Kosztarab" baseAuthorityYear="1967" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Kermicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wroughtoni">
<emphasis id="95BBEA9DBA35B92AFBF3FC45FB12FC24" box="[1046,1207,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="442">K. wroughtoni</emphasis>
(Yang &amp; Kosztarab, 1967)
</taxonomicName>
. In the future, DNA analysis data will help to clarify these relationships. Currently very few specimens of these taxa have been sequenced, but see the last paragraph of the Dsicussion following the descriptions.
</paragraph>
